tam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sybille","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybil","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sybille de Boulogne-sur-Mer was born in 1015, in Boulogne-la-Grasse, Oise, Picardie, France, her father, Lambert de Boulogne, was 5 and her mother, Mathilde De Ponthieu, was 46. She had at least 1 son with Guy Eudes de Dampierre. She died about 1076, in Dampierre, Aube, Champagne-Ardenne, France, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1015–ABT 1076":"1015–umbes 1076","1015–1076":"1015–1076","1010–1072":"1010–1072","1040–1095":"1040–1095","1010–1049":"1010–1049","0970–1054":"0970–1054","1049":"1049","ABT 1076":"umbes 1076","1015":"1015","0970":"0970","1054":"1054","1010":"1010","1076":"1076","1040":"1040","about 1054":"umbes 1054","1095":"1095","1072":"1072","Vincennes, Île-de-France, France":"Vincennes, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Boulogne, Pas-De-Calais, France":"Boulogne-la-Grasse,